{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598407"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:37:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:37:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15469"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15469"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.02,0.02,0.24,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8160"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70417"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8160"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55881"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"422"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1590"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19771"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70417"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with persistent shortness of breath and a dry cough that has lasted for three months. He had a severe COVID-19 infection six months ago, which required hospitalisation and supplemental oxygen. He has a history of hypertension and is on lisinopril. He does not smoke and works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 78/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Auscultation of the lungs revealed fine inspiratory crackles at the bases. A chest X-ray shows reticular opacities in the lower lung zones.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the likely complication of this patient\u0027s COVID-19 infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary fibrosis","Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","Asthma","Bronchiectasis","Pleural effusion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and imaging findings suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E, a known complication of severe COVID-19 infection. It involves the scarring of lung tissue which can lead to persistent respiratory symptoms such as shortness of breath and cough. The presence of fine inspiratory crackles and reticular opacities on chest X-ray supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic obstructive pulmonary disease\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with long-term smoking and is not a direct complication of COVID-19. It is characterised by airflow limitation that is not fully reversible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsthma\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic inflammatory disease of the airways that causes reversible airflow obstruction, often triggered by allergens or irritants. It is not a complication of COVID-19, although COVID-19 can exacerbate pre-existing asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchiectasis\u003C/strong\u003E involves the permanent dilation of bronchi and is usually due to recurrent infections or underlying conditions such as cystic fibrosis. While COVID-19 can cause lung damage, it is not typically associated with the development of bronchiectasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the accumulation of fluid in the pleural space and can occur due to various causes, including heart failure, infection, or malignancy. It is not a common complication of COVID-19, especially in the absence of other suggestive symptoms or findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["COVID-19 can lead to long-term respiratory complications, including pulmonary fibrosis.","Pulmonary fibrosis is characterised by scarring of lung tissue, leading to reduced lung function and respiratory symptoms.","Early recognition and management of post-COVID-19 complications are essential for improving patient outcomes."],"references":["Desai AD, Lavelle M, Boursiquot BC, Wan EY. Long-term complications of COVID-19. Am J Physiol Cell Physiol. 2022 Jan 1;322(1):C1-C11. doi: 10.1152/ajpcell.00375.2021. Epub 2021 Nov 24. PMID: 34817268; PMCID: PMC8721906.","Cascella M, Rajnik M, Aleem A, et al. Features, Evaluation, and Treatment of Coronavirus (COVID-19) [Updated 2023 Aug 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554776/","Alrajhi NN. Post-COVID-19 pulmonary fibrosis: An ongoing concern. Ann Thorac Med. 2023 Oct-Dec;18(4):173-181. doi: 10.4103/atm.atm_7_23. Epub 2023 Oct 17. PMID: 38058790; PMCID: PMC10697304.","Zheng Z, Peng F, Zhou Y. Pulmonary fibrosis: A short- or long-term sequelae of severe COVID-19? Chin Med J Pulm Crit Care Med. 2023 Jun;1(2):77-83. doi: 10.1016/j.pccm.2022.12.002. Epub 2023 Jan 23. PMID: 37388822; PMCID: PMC9988550."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55881"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15469"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisi